The features of the micro-combinatorial sample enable the determination of the optical properties with high spatial and composition resolutions. The width of the focused light spot is ≈\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\approx $$\end{document}0.3 mm that, considering a 20 mm long full range gradient section, corresponds to a resolution of ≈\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\approx $$\end{document} 0.015 in x, which is equivalent with 1.5 at%. In this work we used a step size corresponding to the size of the focused spot. However, the resolution may be increased even further when using step sizes smaller than the spot and applying a method for lateral inhomogeneity41. The equipment used for the measurement allows a lateral step size far below the spot size.

